article.description: No. 3 LSU will take on Arizona State in the championship of the Women's Sports Foundation Classic Friday after the Lady Tigers beat Maine 81-50 on Thursday night to give LSU head coach Pokey Chapman her first career victory.
article.headline: Third-ranked Lady Tigers will face Arizona State
article.linkText: LSU rolls to Women's Sports Foundation Classic final
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. -- Pokey Chatman got the kind of start a coach would want from her own team.

No longer saddled with the interim tag, Chatman watched LSU (No. 2 ESPN/USA Today, No. 3 AP) easily win its season opener Thursday night.

Seimone Augustus scored 17 points and the Tigers beat Maine 81-50 in the Women's Sports Foundation Classic.

"I'm very pleased with the effort from the get-go," Chatman said. "We talked to the kids in the locker room before the game and there didn't seem to be a drop-off.

"Probably the most promising thing that came out of the game was how we played defensively. We played well tonight," she said.

Chatman took over for Sue Gunter last season on an interim basis and led the team to the Final Four. Gunter retired in April after missing the final part of last season with respiratory problems.

Augustus, a preseason All-American, got plenty of help. Sylvia Fowles added 13 points and 11 rebounds in her first college game, and preseason All-American Temeka Johnson had eight points and six rebounds.

All 15 LSU players played at least six minutes, and 14 of them scored.

"We talked to our kids in the locker room about our strength in numbers," Chatman said. "We were able to play the entire bench and relatively do a decent job of taking care of the basketball and executing in the half-court offense.

"It is nice to see those kids step up and gain some confidence against a quality opponent like Maine," she said.

Monica Peterson led Maine with 12 points, and Ashley Underwood added 10.

The Tigers took a 7-0 lead before using a 13-2 run for a commanding 26-12 advantage.

LSU plays Arizona State in Friday's championship game. The Sun Devils State beat Virginia 60-50 earlier Thursday.
